  "prompt": "Does x = 2x, as the limit of x approaches infinity? Why?",
  "response": "No, the equation \\( x = 2x \\) does not hold as the limit of \\( x \\) approaches infinity. Here's why:\n\n1. **Understanding the limit as \\( x \\to \\infty \\):**\n   - As \\( x \\) approaches infinity, both \\( x \\) and \\( 2x \\) grow without bound.\n   - The relationship between \\( x \\) and \\( 2x \\) as \\( x \\to \\infty \\) depends on their relative growth rates.\n\n2. **Comparing \\( x \\) and \\( 2x \\):**\n   - For any finite \\( x \\), \\( 2x \\) is always exactly twice as large as \\( x \\).\n   - As \\( x \\to \\infty \\), \\( 2x \\) still grows at twice the rate of \\( x \\). This means \\( 2x \\) becomes infinitely larger than \\( x \\), not equal to \\( x \\).\n\n3. **Limit behavior:**\n   - The limit of \\( \\frac{2x}{x} \\) as \\( x \\to \\infty \\) is \\( 2 \\), which shows that \\( 2x \\) is always twice as large as \\( x \\) in the limit.\n   - The limit of \\( \\frac{x}{2x} \\) as \\( x \\to \\infty \\) is \\( \\frac{1}{2} \\), confirming that \\( x \\) is always half as large as \\( 2x \\) in the limit.\n\n4. **Conclusion:**\n   - As \\( x \\to \\infty \\), \\( 2x \\) does not equal \\( x \\). Instead, \\( 2x \\) grows at twice the rate of \\( x \\).\n\nThus, \\( x = 2x \\) is not true as \\( x \\to \\infty \\).",
